eople have a weak grasp of the principles that underlie our constitutional system. Crucial questions must be answered: How serious is the situation? What role do schools play in shaping civic behavior? Are current education reform initiatives-such as multiculturalism and school choice-counterproductive? How can schools contribute toward reversing the trend?This volume brings together leading thinkers from a variety of disciplines to probe the relation between a healthy democracy and education. Their original and provocative discussions cut across a range of important topics: the cultivation of democratic values, the formation of social capital in schools and communities, political conflict in a pluralist society, the place of religion in public life, the enduring problems of racial inequality. Gathering together the most current research and thinking on education and civil society, this is a book that deserves the attention of everyone who cares about the quality and future of American democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingxUnited States. 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aCivicsxStudy and teachingxUnited States. 0aCivicsxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aEducationxAims and objectivesxUnited States. 0aEducationxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 0aÉducation civiquexÉtats-Unis. 0aÉducationxFinalitésxÉtats-UnisxUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aRavitch, Diane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aViteritti, Joseph P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z97831105379